Fourth seed Fritz also had to navigate a tricky match, battling past Swiss qualifier Jerome Kym 7-6(3), 6-7(9), 6-4, 6-4 in two hours and 58 minutes.

“I've done a great job of just battling through these matches where it's easy to get frustrated, certain shots aren't working, maybe I'm not playing the level that I want to play,” Fritz said. “But I know, I keep telling myself, ‘Win the match, I get a day off, I can figure it out', and I can keep improving throughout this tournament.”

The defending finalist has now needed four sets in consecutive matches, but he delivered 20 aces against Kym and lost serve just once to avoid too much trouble. He will next take on 21st seed Tomas Machac, a 7-5, 6-3, 6-1 winner against Frenchman Ugo Blanchet earlier in the day.

Fritz will try to make the US Open quarter-finals for the third consecutive year. He recently made the Wimbledon semi-finals for the first time.



